00:57:04,954 --> 00:57:08,390
You're lucky then.

711
00:57:08,458 --> 00:57:12,554
It all gets so...
just such a tangle.

712
00:57:12,629 --> 00:57:15,621
It's a tangle
most people want.

713
00:57:17,300 --> 00:57:19,234
Not me though.

714
00:57:19,302 --> 00:57:23,500
My antics made
a lot of people unhappy.

715
00:57:25,074 --> 00:57:27,406
One horribly so.

716
00:57:31,581 --> 00:57:33,572
For me,

717
00:57:35,285 --> 00:57:40,518
whenever I feel
anything for anyone, l...

718
00:57:40,590 --> 00:57:42,785
I go cold all over.

719
00:57:42,859 --> 00:57:47,853
- What makes you do that?
- Fear, I suppose.

720
00:57:47,931 --> 00:57:53,597
Fear of being burned up...
by love.

721
00:57:54,971 --> 00:57:57,963
Listen to us.

722
00:57:58,041 --> 00:58:03,604
Yes. Aren't we just maudlin?

723
00:58:04,781 --> 00:58:07,181
Maud, you should
let your hair out.

724
00:58:07,250 --> 00:58:10,117
You should let it breathe.
And don't do the ice thing,

725
00:58:10,186 --> 00:58:12,654
'cause you have nothing
to worry about from me.

726
00:58:12,722 --> 00:58:16,419
Christabel said,
" Fear all men."

727
00:58:16,493 --> 00:58:19,951
Well, Christabel
didn't know me.

728
00:58:21,564 --> 00:58:23,828
I don't want to take
anything from you.

729
00:58:25,702 --> 00:58:30,230
So, then, we're both...
perfectly safe.

730
00:58:30,306 --> 00:58:32,570
Right.

731
00:59:21,124 --> 00:59:23,820
How can we bear it?

732
00:59:23,893 --> 00:59:26,953
Every day
we will have less.

733
00:59:34,304 --> 00:59:36,932
Would you rather
have had nothing?

734
00:59:37,006 --> 00:59:38,940
No.

735
00:59:39,008 --> 00:59:43,377
I thank God
that if there had to be
a dragon it was you.

736
01:00:31,961 --> 01:00:34,759
Wait. Wait.

737
01:00:41,938 --> 01:00:46,466
No. I was just trying to get out
from under the covers.
No. No.

738
01:00:46,542 --> 01:00:50,273
This is... We shouldn't
be doing this.
It's dangerous.

739
01:00:52,949 --> 01:00:56,441
Well, I really...
No, because I like you.
I like you a lot.

740
01:00:56,519 --> 01:01:00,979
I just don't want
to blow it here, and...

741
01:01:01,057 --> 01:01:03,457
Well, it doesn't matter
to me, honestly.

742
01:01:03,526 --> 01:01:05,926
What do you mean
it doesn't matter?

743
01:01:12,969 --> 01:01:17,065
Sorry. I think
we're probably just...

744
01:01:17,140 --> 01:01:20,405
In these cramped quarters.
It was a mistake.

745
01:01:22,578 --> 01:01:26,105
Maud. Maud.!

746
01:01:28,551 --> 01:01:30,883
I didn't mean that.

747
01:02:01,718 --> 01:02:04,949
Let's not beat
the thing dead.

748
01:02:05,021 --> 01:02:08,115
It happened, it's over
and we're adults.

749
01:02:08,191 --> 01:02:10,955
Speak for yourself.

750
01:02:11,027 --> 01:02:15,225
I can't imagine
what you're like after you
actually sleep with someone.

751
01:02:19,569 --> 01:02:24,734
Maud, I think
that you are very...

752
01:02:24,807 --> 01:02:27,241
You know?

753
01:02:27,310 --> 01:02:29,676
No, I don't know.

754
01:02:32,482 --> 01:02:35,645
So, what, we're friends
now, is that it?

755
01:02:38,254 --> 01:02:41,314
Yeah. That's a lot.

756
01:02:41,390 --> 01:02:43,358
No, I agree.
It's fine.

757
01:02:43,426 --> 01:02:48,261
Yeah. It's perfect.

758
01:02:48,331 --> 01:02:52,097
Anyway, we're getting
off the track here.

759
01:02:52,168 --> 01:02:55,535
We came to investigate
them, not us.

760
01:03:08,251 --> 01:03:12,119
So what ever happened
to Blanche?
Blanche drowned.

761
01:03:12,188 --> 01:03:14,122
Oh.

762
01:03:15,491 --> 01:03:18,688
Where was Christabel?
We don't know
where she was.

763
01:03:18,761 --> 01:03:21,093
The year before's
a bit blank too.

764
01:03:21,164 --> 01:03:23,997
You don't know where she was
that entire year?

765
01:03:24,066 --> 01:03:26,864
There's some speculation
that she went to France,

766
01:03:26,936 --> 01:03:29,234
but I have nothing
to support that.

767
01:03:31,040 --> 01:03:36,808
Okay, so... Christabel
comes here with Ash
and then disappears.

768
01:03:36,879 --> 01:03:38,904
On paper, at least.

769
01:03:38,981 --> 01:03:42,883
Yes.
And Blanche suicides.

770
01:03:42,952 --> 01:03:45,386
Jesus.

771
01:03:53,029 --> 01:03:55,361
- What are you doing?

772
01:03:55,431 --> 01:03:58,730
It's a poem.
I've been writing it
as I've watched you.

773
01:03:58,801 --> 01:04:00,962
You're not pleased with it?

774
01:04:01,037 --> 01:04:05,599
On the contrary.
I think it perfectly expresses
thejoy I have felt with you.

775
01:04:05,675 --> 01:04:07,905
Then why that?

776
01:04:07,977 --> 01:04:11,003
These feelings...
I want them to survive.

777
01:04:11,080 --> 01:04:14,106
I know I can never
declare all this...

778
01:04:14,183 --> 01:04:17,050
this love.

779
01:04:17,119 --> 01:04:21,954
There. I've said it.
I know it cannot be declared
to the world.

780
01:04:22,024 --> 01:04:25,084
What I may do is scatter
these words from the train...

781
01:04:25,161 --> 01:04:27,425
and hope that
they somehow take root.

782
01:04:27,496 --> 01:04:32,331
They will flourish.
I swear it.

783
01:05:21,317 --> 01:05:24,650
So... what next?

784
01:05:24,720 --> 01:05:26,745
I mean, for you.

785
01:05:26,822 --> 01:05:29,256
I suppose I'll check
through the archives...

786
01:05:29,325 --> 01:05:32,260
and see if there's
any clue at all where Christabel
might have been that year.

787
01:05:32,328 --> 01:05:34,489
Good.

788
01:05:34,563 --> 01:05:38,397
I guess I'll just, uh...

789
01:05:38,467 --> 01:05:41,095
hell, I don't know...

790
01:05:41,170 --> 01:05:44,162
go look up shit
on the microfiche.

791
01:05:44,240 --> 01:05:46,265
Suffer over you.

792
01:05:46,342 --> 01:05:48,833
Good-bye.

793
01:05:48,911 --> 01:05:50,902
See ya.

794
01:07:00,116 --> 01:07:02,846
Lost your way?
Don't do tours here.

795
01:07:02,918 --> 01:07:05,318
Sir George Bailey?
Who wants to know?

796
01:07:05,388 --> 01:07:07,982
Professor Mortimer Cropper,
curator of the Stan Collection,

797
01:07:08,057 --> 01:07:10,958
Robert De Leon University,
Harmony City, New Mexico.

798
01:07:11,027 --> 01:07:13,086
And this is Dr. Wolfe.
Good morning.

799
01:07:13,162 --> 01:07:16,029
I'm a busy man.
My wife's ill.

800
01:07:16,098 --> 01:07:18,862
I can quite understand
that, sir.

801
01:07:18,934 --> 01:07:21,926
Sources have led me to believe
that you may be in possession...

802
01:07:22,004 --> 01:07:26,998
of some documentation
by Randolph Henry Ash.

803
01:07:27,076 --> 01:07:29,544
Whoa.
Don't shoot, please.

804
01:07:29,612 --> 01:07:32,274
Get off my land.

805
01:07:32,348 --> 01:07:35,215
Do you have any idea
what we're talking about here?

806
01:07:35,284 --> 01:07:37,980
Do you? Do you have
any idea how much...

807
01:07:38,054 --> 01:07:40,716
such pieces,
if they existed,

808
01:07:40,790 --> 01:07:43,623
how much
they would be worth?

809
01:07:43,692 --> 01:07:45,717
Worth?

810
01:07:54,236 --> 01:07:56,864
Do you mind if we swing
past the university?

811
01:07:56,939 --> 01:07:59,032
Bit of unfinished
business.

812
01:07:59,108 --> 01:08:03,204
Miss Bailey, I presume.
The accomplice.

813
01:08:03,279 --> 01:08:05,679
The very same.

814
01:08:05,748 --> 01:08:09,582
Good God,you're
like Bonnie and Clyde.

815
01:08:09,652 --> 01:08:11,916
Come on.
I need a picture of her.

816
01:08:11,987 --> 01:08:15,047
I've never seen you
like this.Just go.

817
01:08:15,124 --> 01:08:18,525
Take the Porsche
and go.

818
01:08:47,556 --> 01:08:49,490
Fergus, what?

819
01:08:51,427 --> 01:08:56,592
Uh, if Fergus went out
to get Indian food, I'm gonna...
I'm gonna feel really stupid.

820
01:08:56,665 --> 01:09:00,192
No, he didn't.

821
01:09:00,269 --> 01:09:02,760
India wouldn't be
far enough away, actually.

822
01:09:06,609 --> 01:09:08,736
Come inside. I'll explain.

823
01:09:08,811 --> 01:09:12,975
You sure? I mean,
about me coming in.

824
01:09:13,048 --> 01:09:16,745
Yes, very.

825
01:09:16,819 --> 01:09:19,947
So I left Fergus a message
from Seal Court,

826
01:09:20,022 --> 01:09:22,991
which apparently
put him on our trail,

827
01:09:23,058 --> 01:09:27,620
and he came here looking
for answers... he and Cropper
from the sound of it.

828
01:09:27,696 --> 01:09:30,392
So that was Cropper's
car outside?

829
01:09:30,466 --> 01:09:32,957
I think Fergus
has found something.

830
01:09:33,035 --> 01:09:35,560
He's been spooking
around the museum,

831
01:09:35,638 --> 01:09:39,335
sending out
a bunch of faxes.

832
01:09:39,408 --> 01:09:44,072
I wouldn't be
so quick to do that.

833
01:09:44,146 --> 01:09:46,580
Yeah.

834
01:09:48,050 --> 01:09:52,111
The British Museum
fax log sheet.

835
01:09:52,188 --> 01:09:55,089
"To the University of Muntz
from Fergus Wolfe.

836
01:09:55,157 --> 01:09:58,854
"Subject: Christabel LaMotte.
Information on LaMotte
genealogy.

837
01:09:58,928 --> 01:10:03,194
Request loan of journal
of Sabine de Concasse."

838
01:10:03,265 --> 01:10:05,495
Unfortunately for Fergus,
we have to log our faxes.

839
01:10:05,568 --> 01:10:08,628
You're shameless.

840
01:10:20,416 --> 01:10:23,044
So what are we
gonna do now?

841
01:10:23,118 --> 01:10:26,519
We gonna try to beat 'em
to France, or...

842
01:10:29,725 --> 01:10:32,558
or are we just
gonna stare at each other?

843
01:10:32,628 --> 01:10:34,858
That is the question,
isn't it?

844
01:10:34,930 --> 01:10:36,864
Mm-hmm.

845
01:10:36,932 --> 01:10:39,526
I have another one
for you.
What's that?

846
01:10:39,602 --> 01:10:41,900
What are you really
doing here?

847
01:10:41,971 --> 01:10:44,872
Well, l, uh...

848
01:10:49,778 --> 01:10:51,712
I needed to see your face.

849
01:10:59,255 --> 01:11:03,954
I just want to let you know
that whatever happened
in Whitby,

850
01:11:04,026 --> 01:11:07,928
which unfortunately
was not much,

851
01:11:10,666 --> 01:11:14,158
is not because
anything that you did.

852
01:11:16,372 --> 01:11:18,306
Not at all.

853
01:11:21,010 --> 01:11:23,911
I just didn't want
to jump into something.

854
01:11:25,114 --> 01:11:29,949
I mean, I did
and I do... want to.

855
01:11:31,287 --> 01:11:33,278
Badly.

856
01:11:36,792 --> 01:11:39,955
I just didn't
want to mess this up.

857
01:11:43,132 --> 01:11:46,590
And I just want to see...

858
01:11:46,669 --> 01:11:52,266
I want to see if there's
an us in you and me.

859
01:11:57,212 --> 01:11:59,874
Would-Would you like that?

860
01:12:09,425 --> 01:12:11,893
I'll take that
as a yes.

861
01:12:41,023 --> 01:12:46,086
Ah, oui. Excusez-moi.
Nous sommes confreres.

862
01:12:46,161 --> 01:12:48,095
When will she be back?

863
01:12:49,531 --> 01:12:52,364
Could you check for us?

864
01:13:18,961 --> 01:13:21,725
- She will return on Thursday.
- Okay.

865
01:13:21,797 --> 01:13:23,731
Au revoir.
Merci.

866
01:13:23,799 --> 01:13:28,896
You and your shoplifting, huh?
I can't take you anywhere.

867
01:13:42,418 --> 01:13:47,287
" Dear Professor Wolfe:
Since I wrote to you last,
I've made another discovery.

868
01:13:47,356 --> 01:13:49,824
"Amongst Sabine's papers
was her journal...

869
01:13:49,892 --> 01:13:53,919
"in which she writes
about LaMotte's visit
to Brittany in 1 859...

870
01:13:53,996 --> 01:13:57,432
and the subsequent arrival
of a mysterious visitor. "

871
01:15:02,097 --> 01:15:07,433
I know how things are.
I wish to help you.

872
01:15:07,503 --> 01:15:10,267
You know how things are, do you?
Tell me, Cousin Sabine,

873
01:15:10,339 --> 01:15:13,797
how do you think
things are with me?

874
01:15:13,876 --> 01:15:16,003
I'm a grown woman.
You are a girl.

875
01:15:16,078 --> 01:15:18,342
I do not desire
any help from you.

876
01:15:26,688 --> 01:15:30,249
 Christabel's condition
became worse...

877
01:15:30,325 --> 01:15:33,920
after she received word
from London...

878
01:15:33,996 --> 01:15:37,397
that her close friend
had died.

879
01:16:12,000 --> 01:16:14,969
She left England
because she was pregnant,

880
01:16:15,037 --> 01:16:16,971
and Blanche
committed suicide.

881
01:16:22,778 --> 01:16:24,837
What happened to the baby?

882
01:16:24,913 --> 01:16:27,404
It must have been stillborn.

883
01:16:27,482 --> 01:16:29,416
Or died.

884
01:16:29,484 --> 01:16:31,714
Maybe it was taken in
by nuns or a local family.

885
01:16:31,787 --> 01:16:35,120
And brought up here.

886
01:16:35,190 --> 01:16:39,251
I'd like to think that,
but I wonder.

887
01:16:39,328 --> 01:16:43,526
- You wonder what?
- I don't know. I just...

888
01:16:43,599 --> 01:16:49,560
She comes here alone, hears
that Blanche has killed herself.

889
01:16:49,638 --> 01:16:51,833
She's pregnant, distraught.

890
01:16:54,776 --> 01:16:56,710
Geez.

891
01:16:56,778 --> 01:16:59,338
I mean, I've no
evidence for it.

892
01:16:59,414 --> 01:17:02,110
Can you imagine
how she must have felt?

893
01:17:03,518 --> 01:17:06,180
Yes, I can.

894
01:17:17,733 --> 01:17:20,930
So when do we see
Christabel next?

895
01:17:21,003 --> 01:17:25,406
Autumn, 1 860,
in her references
to the Vestal Lights.

896
01:17:25,474 --> 01:17:29,410
It was a group of women
who used to meet with mediums
on a regular basis.

897
01:17:29,478 --> 01:17:33,574
Really? You know,
Ash hated spiritualists.
Pretty openly.

898
01:17:33,649 --> 01:17:36,584
You think
that's a connection
we're tracking down?

899
01:17:36,652 --> 01:17:38,643
I don't know.

900
01:17:48,030 --> 01:17:51,659
Please, make a circle
with your hands.

901
01:17:57,172 --> 01:17:59,106
Close your eyes.

902
01:18:04,479 --> 01:18:07,676
White earth. Valley.

903
01:18:07,749 --> 01:18:11,048
A waterfall.

904
01:18:11,119 --> 01:18:14,282
A child. Love.

905
01:18:14,356 --> 01:18:18,850
Two people. Deception.

906
01:18:18,927 --> 01:18:23,489
Letters. Two people.

907
01:18:24,933 --> 01:18:28,334
Words. Death.

908
01:18:28,403 --> 01:18:30,997
What have you done?

909
01:18:31,073 --> 01:18:33,871
A field.

910
01:18:33,942 --> 01:18:36,911
Where is the child?

911
01:18:42,184 --> 01:18:46,120
What have you done
with the child?

912
01:18:46,188 --> 01:18:49,521
You have made
a murderess of me.

913
01:18:57,232 --> 01:19:00,292
"I understood at the time
that Mr. Ash was inquiring...

914
01:19:00,368 --> 01:19:03,804
"after the spirit of
a departed child ofhis own,

915
01:19:03,872 --> 01:19:06,864
"but I am told that
this could not be the case...

916
01:19:06,942 --> 01:19:09,672
as Mr. Ash is childless."

917
01:19:14,349 --> 01:19:19,616
Was there any mention
of Heloise in your research?

918
01:19:19,688 --> 01:19:23,624
I don't know...
nor do I care.

919
01:19:23,692 --> 01:19:26,456
Look, I've got to get back.

920
01:19:28,230 --> 01:19:33,167
What's going on?
Nothing. I'm just tired,
that's all, so I should...

921
01:19:33,235 --> 01:19:35,601
Come on.
What's wrong, seriously?

922
01:19:37,205 --> 01:19:40,732
I don't actually
want to discover
anything else about them.

923
01:19:40,809 --> 01:19:43,710
You know?

924
01:19:43,779 --> 01:19:47,078
I'm finding things out
that are just...

925
01:19:47,149 --> 01:19:51,051
It's horrible when you
think about it really...
men and women together.

926
01:19:53,488 --> 01:19:56,389
She gave up her life,
didn't she?

927
01:19:56,458 --> 01:19:59,894
A perfectly decent life
that I've always admired.
And for what? For nothing.

928
01:19:59,961 --> 01:20:02,589
No. Not nothing.

929
01:20:02,664 --> 01:20:07,727
Oh, really? For what then?
A child who died, a lover
drowned, and to what end?

930
01:20:07,803 --> 01:20:11,637
She and Ash,
my own parents...

931
01:20:11,706 --> 01:20:15,039
and every relationship
I've ever had...

932
01:20:15,110 --> 01:20:20,207
It's all doomed.
We can't seem to help but
just tear each other apart.

933
01:20:20,282 --> 01:20:24,446
Well, what about us?
You didn't include us.
What about that?

934
01:20:25,620 --> 01:20:27,554
Look, l...

935
01:20:29,124 --> 01:20:31,592
I can't think about
anything right now.

936
01:20:34,663 --> 01:20:36,597
So, okay.

937
01:20:36,665 --> 01:20:39,998
So this is the, uh...
this is the icy pull-back
part then, huh?

938
01:20:40,068 --> 01:20:44,198
- What?
- You know, you get close,
you pull away, you get...

939
01:20:44,272 --> 01:20:46,638
I mean, this is part
of the pattern, right?

940
01:20:46,708 --> 01:20:51,111
- What are you talking about?
- Your fear of men mantra
from Yorkshire.

941
01:20:51,179 --> 01:20:53,807
That's what
I'm talking about.

942
01:20:53,882 --> 01:20:56,976
I get it. It's cool.
If that's the way you play it,
that's the way play it.

943
01:20:57,052 --> 01:20:59,486
Do you honestly believe that?

944
01:20:59,554 --> 01:21:04,856
Is that what you think
this is to me? A game? Is it?

945
01:21:09,431 --> 01:21:13,265
Well, finally, then,
all this talk of us really
comes to nothing, doesn't it?

946
01:21:13,335 --> 01:21:16,168
Yes, I guess you're right.
It's nothing.

947
01:21:53,208 --> 01:21:56,268
Dear Professor Blackadder:

948
01:21:56,344 --> 01:21:59,711
I did try to tell you
about my discovery before...

949
01:21:59,781 --> 01:22:02,716
but found that I couldn't.

950
01:22:02,784 --> 01:22:06,413
Please read these two letters,

951
01:22:06,488 --> 01:22:09,787
and you will begin
to understand.

952
01:22:09,858 --> 01:22:13,453
I'm sorry for deceiving you.

953
01:22:13,528 --> 01:22:17,123
Sincerely, Roland Michell.

954
01:22:33,248 --> 01:22:37,548
And it's well documented
that Ellen Ash set a box
on Ash's coffin...

955
01:22:37,619 --> 01:22:39,780
a kind of sealed container.

956
01:22:39,854 --> 01:22:41,981
We'd always imagined
it was just trinkets,

957
01:22:42,057 --> 01:22:45,754
but in the light of Michell's
discovery, who knows what
treasures might be buried there.

958
01:22:45,827 --> 01:22:48,728
That box is mine, isn't it?
It's my property.

959
01:22:48,797 --> 01:22:51,595
 Cropper]
Once you get it from Lord Ash,
it's absolutely yours.

960
01:22:51,666 --> 01:22:53,964
Until then,
we keep it a secret.

961
01:22:54,035 --> 01:22:56,868
Any discovery amongst
Lord Ash's things,

962
01:22:56,938 --> 01:23:00,738
and, uh...
and I purchase it from you.

963
01:23:00,809 --> 01:23:03,744
It's all above board,
no one the wiser.

964
01:23:03,812 --> 01:23:06,007
Cropper, are you
absolutely sure of that?

965
01:23:06,081 --> 01:23:08,572
Listen.
Uh, where is it?

966
01:23:08,650 --> 01:23:10,777
Yeah. "I place this
letter in his hands,

967
01:23:10,852 --> 01:23:13,286
"and if ghouls
dig it up again,

968
01:23:13,355 --> 01:23:16,722
then perhaps justice
will be done when I am
not here to see it. "

969
01:23:26,301 --> 01:23:32,035
Dear Madam: We are older now
and my fires at last are out.

970
01:23:32,107 --> 01:23:35,907
I know that you are
more than aware of my name,

971
01:23:35,977 --> 01:23:39,674
but I find you must see it
in print one last time.

972
01:23:39,748 --> 01:23:44,208
It has been made known to me
that your husband
is near to death,

973
01:23:44,285 --> 01:23:49,120
so I have writ down,
for his eyes only, some things.

974
01:23:49,190 --> 01:23:54,287
I find I cannot say what things
and have sealed the letter.

975
01:23:54,362 --> 01:23:58,765
If you wish to read it,
it is in your hands,

976
01:23:58,833 --> 01:24:02,997
though I must hope that he
will see it first and decide.

977
01:24:03,071 --> 01:24:08,373
I have done great harm,
though I meant none to you.

978
01:25:02,630 --> 01:25:06,191
I'll see they get back,
no questions asked.

979
01:25:07,902 --> 01:25:10,564
You're more enterprising
than I gave you credit for.

980
01:25:10,638 --> 01:25:12,731
Was there a compliment
in there somewhere?

981
01:25:12,807 --> 01:25:16,004
Hmm? Yes, probably.

982
01:25:18,179 --> 01:25:22,138
What I can't believe
is Fergus Wolfe
conniving with Cropper.

983
01:25:22,217 --> 01:25:24,378
I thought I was
a better judge of men.

984
01:25:24,452 --> 01:25:28,013
Well, see, that's
where you went wrong. You
gave him credit for being one.

985
01:25:30,825 --> 01:25:33,623
Thank you.

986
01:25:37,165 --> 01:25:39,759
Hi.
Hi.

987
01:25:39,834 --> 01:25:42,359
Thank you
for coming.
Sure.

988
01:25:42,437 --> 01:25:46,635
I believe
that may be her.

989
01:25:46,708 --> 01:25:49,939
l, uh... I'm sorry.
No, I'm sorry.

990
01:25:50,011 --> 01:25:53,606
No, listen.
I lost it totally.
It wasn't you.

991
01:25:53,681 --> 01:25:58,050
So, why don't we all
talk some strategy?

992
01:25:58,119 --> 01:26:00,849
Let me introduce
you to, uh...
All right.

993
01:26:00,922 --> 01:26:05,086
Professor Blackadder, Paola,
this is Dr. Bailey.

994
01:26:05,160 --> 01:26:07,651
Maud.
Maud.

995
01:26:07,729 --> 01:26:10,095
How do you do?

996
01:26:10,165 --> 01:26:15,068
So, do we really think that
Cropper's capable of something
like this, of robbing a grave?

997
01:26:20,408 --> 01:26:23,605
It's creepy, the idea
of opening a grave.

998
01:26:23,678 --> 01:26:25,612
Let's just keep going.

999
01:26:25,680 --> 01:26:28,979
Jesus.

1000
01:26:29,050 --> 01:26:32,508
"The moping owl does
to the moon complain."
Complain.

1001
01:26:34,856 --> 01:26:37,188
Are you ready?

1002
01:26:37,258 --> 01:26:40,455
Yeah.
Hold the light up.

1003
01:26:57,278 --> 01:27:00,179
Fergus! Fergus!
 Is that it?

1004
01:27:00,248 --> 01:27:03,649
Yes. It's gotta be.

1005
01:27:03,718 --> 01:27:07,119
I found it, Fergus.
I found it.

1006
01:27:13,995 --> 01:27:18,694
Oh, my God.
I found it, Fergus.

1007
01:27:18,766 --> 01:27:20,666
Great!

1008
01:27:22,237 --> 01:27:25,229
Hey, Cropper.!
Cropper.!

1009
01:27:31,412 --> 01:27:34,210
This has nothing
to do with you people.

1010
01:27:42,724 --> 01:27:46,387
Wait!
Get off of me!
Get off of me!

1011
01:27:46,461 --> 01:27:49,396
No you don't!

1012
01:27:49,464 --> 01:27:52,490
Traitor!
Bloody conniver!
Please!

1013
01:27:56,170 --> 01:27:57,933
Wait!

1014
01:27:59,674 --> 01:28:03,508
What are you doin'?

1015
01:28:18,293 --> 01:28:22,024
Oh, shit.

1016
01:28:26,100 --> 01:28:28,295
Are you sure
we should be doing this?

1017
01:28:28,369 --> 01:28:30,929
I told Blackadder
we'd just take a look...

1018
01:28:31,005 --> 01:28:33,633
before we handed it over
to the museum.

1019
01:28:33,708 --> 01:28:36,199
Can you hold that there?

1020
01:28:53,328 --> 01:28:55,888
Maud, look at this.

1021
01:29:11,713 --> 01:29:13,943
It's her handwriting.

1022
01:29:42,276 --> 01:29:45,677
" My dear, my dear:

1023
01:29:45,747 --> 01:29:48,147
"They tell me
you are very ill.

1024
01:29:48,216 --> 01:29:51,083
"Perhaps I am wrong
to disturb you at this time...

1025
01:29:51,152 --> 01:29:54,952
"with unseasonable memories,

1026
01:29:55,022 --> 01:30:00,392
"but I find I have, after all,
a thing which I must tell you.

1027
01:30:02,096 --> 01:30:04,758
"You will say it should have
been told 20 years ago,

1028
01:30:04,832 --> 01:30:07,801
"but I could, or would, not.

1029
01:30:09,270 --> 01:30:11,898
"You have a daughter...

1030
01:30:13,207 --> 01:30:15,937
"who is well and married...

1031
01:30:16,010 --> 01:30:19,138
"and the mother
of a beautiful boy.

1032
01:30:19,213 --> 01:30:21,977
"I've sent you a picture.

1033
01:30:26,988 --> 01:30:30,185
"You will see she resembles
both her parents,

1034
01:30:30,258 --> 01:30:33,887
"neither of whom she knows
to be her parent.

1035
01:30:33,961 --> 01:30:39,558
"When I said
at that terrible seance that
you had made a murderess of me,

1036
01:30:39,634 --> 01:30:44,401
"I was speaking of poor Blanche,
who then torments me daily,

1037
01:30:45,673 --> 01:30:49,165
"and I thought,
'Let him think so then...

1038
01:30:49,243 --> 01:30:51,768
"ifhe knows me so little. '

1039
01:30:53,781 --> 01:30:56,045
"I had a secret fear, you see.

1040
01:30:56,117 --> 01:30:58,551
"I was afraid that
you would wish to take her...

1041
01:30:58,619 --> 01:31:01,053
"you and your wife...
for your own.

1042
01:31:01,122 --> 01:31:03,420
But I could not let her go."

1043
01:31:03,491 --> 01:31:06,756
Over here.

1044
01:31:06,828 --> 01:31:08,887
And so I hid her from you...

1045
01:31:08,963 --> 01:31:11,431
and you from her.

1046
01:31:12,934 --> 01:31:16,426
She loves her adoptive
parents most deeply.

1047
01:31:16,504 --> 01:31:19,098
Me, she does not love.

1048
01:31:19,173 --> 01:31:24,406
So I am punished now,
living at Seal Court with them
and watching her grow.

1049
01:31:24,479 --> 01:31:27,778
I have been angry
for so long...

1050
01:31:27,849 --> 01:31:29,976
with all of us,

1051
01:31:30,051 --> 01:31:32,349
and now, near the end,

1052
01:31:32,420 --> 01:31:36,083
I think of you again
with clear love.

1053
01:31:36,157 --> 01:31:39,126
Did we not...

1054
01:31:39,193 --> 01:31:43,562
Did you not flame
and I catch fire?

1055
01:31:43,631 --> 01:31:46,862
Was not the love
that we found...

1056
01:31:46,934 --> 01:31:49,732
worth the tempest
that it brewed?

1057
01:31:49,804 --> 01:31:53,604
I feel it was.
I know it was.

1058
01:31:53,674 --> 01:31:58,407
"If you are able or willing,
please send me a sign
that you have read this.

1059
01:31:58,479 --> 01:32:02,916
"I dare not ask
if you forgive.

1060
01:32:04,051 --> 01:32:06,315
Christabel LaMotte."

1061
01:32:09,524 --> 01:32:12,459
Ash had never read this.

1062
01:32:12,527 --> 01:32:15,428
He never knew
he had a child.

1063
01:32:15,496 --> 01:32:19,023
You're descended from both
Christabel and Ash.

1064
01:32:21,335 --> 01:32:25,169
My God.

1065
01:32:25,239 --> 01:32:31,007
All these clues,
they're for you.

1066
01:32:32,947 --> 01:32:34,972
For us.

1067
01:32:48,462 --> 01:32:50,487
You're so beautiful.

1068
01:33:20,928 --> 01:33:26,195
There are things that happen,
not spoken or written of.

1069
01:33:26,267 --> 01:33:28,963
Apoet walked out
one summer's day...

1070
01:33:29,036 --> 01:33:32,437
seeking forgiveness
from a love long lost.

1071
01:33:33,941 --> 01:33:36,637
He found
something else instead.

1072
01:33:38,079 --> 01:33:40,843
This is how it was.

1073
01:33:49,156 --> 01:33:52,216
Morning.
Good morning.

1074
01:33:52,293 --> 01:33:54,227
What's your name?

1075
01:33:54,295 --> 01:33:58,698
May Bailey, but I have
another name I don't like.

1076
01:33:58,766 --> 01:34:03,760
Do you? What's that?

1077
01:34:03,838 --> 01:34:06,204
Maya Thomason Bailey.

1078
01:34:11,746 --> 01:34:13,737
Well...

1079
01:34:16,050 --> 01:34:19,952
Maya was the, uh...

1080
01:34:20,021 --> 01:34:22,717
the mother of Hermes,

1081
01:34:22,790 --> 01:34:25,054
and I know a waterfall
called Thomason.

1082
01:34:25,126 --> 01:34:28,425
A waterfall? Really?
Yes.

1083
01:34:28,496 --> 01:34:33,900
In Yorkshire.
With a lovely cave
hidden behind it.

1084
01:34:36,003 --> 01:34:37,937
Where do you live?

1085
01:34:38,005 --> 01:34:39,973
I live in that house
down there.

1086
01:34:40,041 --> 01:34:43,738
And my mother lives there
and my father...

1087
01:34:43,811 --> 01:34:45,836
and my two brothers.

1088
01:34:45,913 --> 01:34:48,575
Oh, and my Aunt Christabel too.

1089
01:34:50,351 --> 01:34:52,979
Yes, I think
I know your mother.

1090
01:34:56,724 --> 01:34:59,090
You have
the true look of her.

1091
01:34:59,160 --> 01:35:04,257
No one else says that.
I think I look like my father.

1092
01:35:06,200 --> 01:35:08,691
You look like
your father too.

1093
01:35:11,405 --> 01:35:13,669
Can you make daisy chains?

1094
01:35:13,741 --> 01:35:16,608
Yes.

1095
01:35:19,447 --> 01:35:22,416
Yes, I'll make you a crown.

1096
01:35:24,251 --> 01:35:29,086
But, um... will you
give me a lock of your hair?

1097
01:35:30,891 --> 01:35:33,553
Like fairy story.

1098
01:35:35,396 --> 01:35:37,626
Just so.

1099
01:35:48,709 --> 01:35:52,645
Now, would you
take this note...

1100
01:35:52,713 --> 01:35:55,011
to your aunt.

1101
01:35:56,650 --> 01:35:59,551
Tell her that
you saw a poet...

1102
01:35:59,620 --> 01:36:01,986
who was coming
to meet her...

1103
01:36:02,056 --> 01:36:04,286
but met you instead.

1104
01:36:04,358 --> 01:36:06,485
I'll try to remember.

1105
01:36:08,295 --> 01:36:10,286
Thank you.

